<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">06, Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in SoCal built-in refrigerators</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Cooling / Warm Temperatures</h3>
        <p>Check the condenser first (Sub-Zero and many other built-ins). If condenser is clean, it's likely the compressor, sealed system, or evaporator. On Sub-Zero: which section is warm? Refrigerator-only warm = refrigerator compressor. Freezer-only warm = freezer compressor. Both sections warm = control board or power issue. This differential diagnosis is only possible on Sub-Zero's dual compressor system.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Error Codes on Display</h3>
        <p>Modern built-in refrigerators (Sub-Zero, Miele, Thermador, Gaggenau, Liebherr) display error codes for specific faults, temperature sensor failure, door seal error, compressor fault, fan motor fault. We interpret these codes for the specific brand and model before touching any components. Many "error code" calls turn out to be sensor or control board issues rather than mechanical failures.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Ice Maker Not Producing</h3>
        <p>Built-in refrigerator ice makers fail for the same reasons as standard models, water inlet valve, ice maker module, temperature sensor, but access is different and parts are brand-specific. Sub-Zero ice makers are in the fresh food section (not the freezer), which is an unusual configuration. Miele and Thermador ice makers have different module designs from standard residential units.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Water Dispenser / Filter Issues</h3>
        <p>Water line freeze, failed water inlet valve, or a water filter that's overdue for replacement and restricting flow. Many LA built-in refrigerators have filtered water dispensers, the filter should be replaced every 6 months. A severely expired filter often causes low water pressure that's mistaken for a valve failure.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Compressor Noise / Vibration</h3>
        <p>Built-in refrigerators are designed to run quietly, any significant noise change is worth diagnosing. A grinding compressor sound indicates bearing wear. A clicking sound that repeats every few minutes is a compressor trying and failing to start (thermal overload cycling). A gurgling or hissing is usually normal refrigerant flow. We distinguish these on-site before recommending any compressor work.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Seal / Gasket Failure</h3>
        <p>A failed door gasket on a built-in refrigerator causes warm temperatures and excessive compressor cycling, the refrigerator works harder to maintain temperature because conditioned air is escaping. Panel-ready models with custom cabinetry panels have a different gasket system than standard stainless units. Gasket replacement requires careful removal of the door panel without damaging the finish.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07, Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Bel Air · Estate Kitchen · Sub-Zero 648PRO Built-In Side-by-Side</div>
        <h3>"Refrigerator section is warm but freezer is perfectly fine, been like this two days"</h3>
        <p>Failed refrigerator-section compressor on a Sub-Zero 648PRO in a Bel Air estate kitchen. The dual compressor architecture made the diagnosis immediate, warm refrigerator with normal freezer on a Sub-Zero means the refrigerator compressor has failed while the freezer compressor continues operating normally. This is the textbook dual compressor failure pattern that only applies to Sub-Zero.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Confirmed refrigerator compressor failure by checking compressor start relay and measuring compressor winding resistance, open circuit on start winding. Replaced Sub-Zero refrigerator section compressor assembly with OEM part. Recharged refrigerant per Sub-Zero specification. Tested refrigerator section temperature recovery over 4-hour observation period, reached and held 37°F target. Freezer section unaffected throughout, maintained 0°F continuously. The homeowner noted the repair was significantly less than the $18,000 replacement quote they had received from another company. Total repair: $890.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills · Remodeled Kitchen · Miele MasterCool KFN 9855 iDE</div>
        <h3>"Error F7 on the display, no idea what it means, refrigerator still cooling but showing alarm"</h3>
        <p>Failed temperature sensor (NTC sensor) on a Miele MasterCool built-in refrigerator. The F7 error on Miele refrigerators indicates a temperature sensor fault, the sensor that monitors the refrigerator compartment temperature had failed out of spec. The refrigerator was still cooling adequately because the compressor was defaulting to a fixed cycle rate, but without accurate temperature monitoring the control system was alarming and the ice maker had shut down as a safety precaution.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Decoded F7 error for this specific Miele model, confirmed NTC temperature sensor failure by resistance measurement (reading open circuit vs. expected 10kΩ at 25°C). Replaced NTC sensor with Miele OEM part. Cleared error codes. Verified temperature control accuracy over 2-hour observation, refrigerator maintaining 36–38°F within 0.5°F of setpoint. Ice maker reactivated automatically after sensor replacement. Homeowner had been living with the alarm for two weeks, the repair was a 90-minute visit. Total repair: $280.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Coast (OC) · Coastal Estate · Thermador T36BB910SS Column Refrigerator</div>
        <h3>"Refrigerator runs constantly, never seems to shut off, and the compressor is warm to the touch"</h3>
        <p>Clogged condenser on a Thermador column refrigerator in a Newport Coast estate kitchen that hadn't been serviced since installation approximately four years prior. The condenser, located behind the front kick grille in this front-ventilated built-in configuration, had accumulated four years of dust and debris (coastal humidity accelerates fin fouling), severely restricting airflow. The compressor was running continuously because it couldn't shed heat effectively and was struggling to maintain the setpoint temperature. The warm compressor surface was from thermal overload, not failure.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Removed kick grille and inspected condenser, found heavy dust accumulation reducing effective fin surface by approximately 70%. Deep cleaned condenser with refrigerator-safe coil cleaner and compressed air. Measured compressor operating temperature before and after: dropped from 185°F to 112°F (normal operating range). Refrigerator resumed normal compressor cycling (on/off pattern) within 45 minutes of cleaning. Also checked door gaskets, found slight compression loss on lower left corner; recommended replacement within 6 months but not urgent. Total service: $89 diagnostic + $95 condenser cleaning service = $184. Enrolled in annual maintenance plan, coastal installations especially benefit from yearly condenser service.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Westlake Village (Ventura) · Custom Kitchen · Sub-Zero 736TCI Integrated</div>
        <h3>"Ice maker stopped working, no ice for three weeks"</h3>
        <p>Failed water inlet valve on a Sub-Zero 736TCI integrated refrigerator in a Westlake Village home. The 736TCI is a panel-ready integrated model, it accepts a full-overlay custom panel that matches the kitchen cabinetry, making it visually indistinguishable from the surrounding cabinets. Access to the ice maker requires careful navigation around the cabinetry interface without contacting the painted custom panel, a routine service procedure on integrated models but one that requires specific experience.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Confirmed water inlet valve failure by testing valve solenoid resistance, open circuit, valve not opening to allow water into the ice maker. Replaced Sub-Zero water inlet valve with OEM part. Careful panel handling throughout, no contact with the painted custom panel surface. Ran ice maker through three production cycles to confirm consistent cube production. Also checked the water filter, found it 14 months past its replacement date, which had been contributing to reduced water flow. Replaced filter simultaneously. Ice maker producing at full capacity, 8–10 cubes per cycle. Total repair: $310.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

